The Prague Stock Exchange ended with fewer points at the end of the day
After the rapid fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected its losses.
Transactions on ČEZ’s shares reached approximately half the value they have on a normal day.
The Prague Stock Exchange, at the beginning of Tuesday, immediately reacted to Monday's fall when it fell to roughly 6%.
The decline this time is due to the fall of stocks on Wall Street.
Also here is expressed the reaction of the market to the outcome of the vote of the American Assembly of Representatives that refused to support the financial sector secretary’s stabilization plan.
Decline of shares in Asia
Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic drop on Tuesday, although over the course of the day the index finally diminished part of the losses.
The Hong Kong Hang Seng Stock Exchange index over its financial day scored nearly four percent, although it later attenuated its losses reducing the decline by almost 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index that follows Chinese stock movements on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange fell 3.8 percent, in Shanghai markets were closed.
The shares of the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent but, in the end, losses dropped to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwan Stock Exchange, according to the Index secretary, fell to 3.6 percent.
“The planned rescue actions in the U.S. are unsafe and this influences the financial market around the world,” said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Currency Office.
Although Hong Kong is a part of China, it alone determines its monetary policy, that is, without dependence on the Central Bank of China.
Hong Kong’s interest rates are at the same level as those in the United States.
U.S. lawmakers should re-meet as soon as possible, Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said, and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that falls will be felt in other countries.
Bloody Bath of American Stocks
On Monday, the U.S. Assembly of Representatives rejected the aid plan to the financial system to which $700 billion (nearly 12 trillion crowns) should be devoted.
Legislators thus ignored President George Bush’s invitation to support his plan.
For Bush, the plan would solve the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, American stocks experienced a bloody bath and mainly the stock index picked up the biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index dropped to nearly seven percent, with a similar volume drop last recorded in 1987.
The index dropped before it was announced but as soon as it was shown that the assembly’s proposal was not going forward, the index began to drop freely.
Congress withdraws: U.S. government can inject $700 billion into banking
