The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not going to be long before it arrives.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobile.cz.
The rest also confirmed the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming fee regulation, it is likely to come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS that they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competence that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, said that there is no longer a place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with their own network, it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be quite difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still one possibility - the virtual operator.
Precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a marked price drop to which the classical operators had to react.
At the same time, even before the entry of sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
There is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to attract more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
Furthermore, after Mobilking is the Penta group which, apart from that, is the owner of U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to concentrate on many more specific target groups.
Furthermore, in order for them to work effectively, they have a lot fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large expenses in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators are typically profiled at low cost – they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that, however, are often counteracted with the offering of more tight services.
Thus, for example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half the cheapest compared to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a good hit as well the bet on a nothing trivial goal group.
This operator is specifically aimed at the man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – it’s the operator he likes and can be trusted,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works with this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept like that of Poland could hook up in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický said: “The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
Furthermore, from the point of view of the service offering is relatively saturated."
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in Czech Republic doesn’t seem too hopeful.
Rather, it’s about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region,” said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone conversation with mobil.cz.
Indirectly he assured that current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not lean to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competition arises.
Interest in launching a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real Telefónica O2 competitor in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, in order to be able to offer our customers not only fixed phone services but also mobile phone services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have repeatedly met with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have succeeded in advancing the meetings,” group spokesman Pavel Kaidl said.
Then, maybe they flash better times.
It appears that, for informal information, the first official operator would possibly have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“Right now, we believe that the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with some complex and serious project in this field,” Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesman for Telefónica O2, told mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market refers to other operators.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2's opinion, adds: "To date we have not recorded any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop."
“In the T-Mobile network, it will be difficult to find a virtual operator by the end of the year.
At this time we should already have on the table some specific contract that would be possible to study in such a short horizon."
Vodafone focuses its attention rather on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this as regards spending and infrastructure sharing.
We consider it to be the biggest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to set up a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a price drop and thereby a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier to enter the competition?
When traders want to get something, they are able to pull the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on ČTÚ was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is attested to public information accessible on the ČTÚ websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: “In addition, the competitive environment in the mobile market has not long been open to a fourth operator.
With regard to the character of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would entail great requirements for him and, above all, for his services."
That is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Procurement (ÚOHS).
However, it expressed its typical stance to this problem.
“A virtual operator’s entry into the mobile market would be possible after a contract on renting the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator was closed.
Until today no agreement has been concluded as the offer of the potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for the classic operators,” added Kristián Chalupa, of the UOHS Department of Foreign Affairs.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers, it is more than a consideration, but they should note that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: “Abroad where virtual operators operate normally, we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the price drop of mobile services.”
Obviously, pressure as to the proper functioning of the market media and the price drop do not fall within the interest of the UOHS.
Really how dramatically shocking this whole case is is in the dissonant reactions resulting from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at the gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
“The Office has found no signs of unfair competition in this regard and has therefore no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore, have no corresponding rise in liability in their market operations.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunications regulators,” Chalupa added.
Interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many conflicting points.
There is obviously an analysis of relevant markets drawn up by ČTÚ according to which telecommunications are a single market from the point of view of the commercial tender.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech traders have a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another vision – for a virtual operator to emerge, agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for UOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise strikingly similarly.
Current complaints from stakeholders (including the aforementioned GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with operators they clash with many similar obstacles.
Charging responsibility in the ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the UOHS washes hands on all this matter.
We have met him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law for the expansion of the ČTÚ competition in the field of commercial tenders was introduced recently, which was not carried out, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This should be well known to the UOHS representatives, but it is obvious that their interests are elsewhere.
Everything goes well, when nobody looks
At the same time, it unnoticedly continues to work something like a pseudovirtual operator that in the Czech mobile phone networks already exists a few.
These are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, only a part are public.
These are typically companies that engage in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Usually only a few chosen companies get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same by ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that trading conditions in all Czech mobile phone operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases such as the ones cited were discovered, we could talk about breach of contractual terms that could translate to the end of collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová responded to the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they earn profits that are not despicable and, at the same time - unlike real virtual traders - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns us of the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible so much percent of customers.
They must also accept that your phone’s SIM card is not in your name so they can’t absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of the carriers.”
This is precisely what should seem to the ČTÚ minimally strange.
There is also a new question for UOHS.
If mobile operators surround their eyes in this type of procedure, why do they block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activities and if it is not willing it should not be content with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As it was already clear in the text, the virtual operator’s entry into the mobile phone market brought a significant decline in services prices.
At the same time, in virtually every country where the virtual operator emerged, the classical operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this break-up.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, eventually too saturated, problems with service quality, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have intervened at this time and in none of the cases defended operators but their customers.
Whether it was with formal measures or informal pressure they managed the first virtual operator to emerge and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all of this case happens as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we cannot fail to be impressed by the confusion of attributes in these cases.
But let's not despair.
If this backstage information is correct and the virtual operator actually gets to these lands, then the Czech mobile phone market will likely start moving again.
If one of the carriers lets any virtual mobile operator in, it will be difficult for the UOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we may stop calling it more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the official Czech anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the day of official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the National Theatre orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - two versions that are Solos, one to male voice and one to female voice, one with choir and another instrumental.
The song is held by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the arrangements of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek regards this national Czech song as one of the most beautiful anthems.
The Czech Radio has previously said that it has intentionally chosen Solos singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
“From the beginning, I have tried with both of them and then, too, with the Choir to fix themselves in the diction so that the text was well understood, so that it was consistent,” he said.
The official Czech anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, My Home sounded for the first time in 1834 on the tables of the State Theatre in the original Czech work Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it theirs.
The first strofe of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
