The Prague MHD takes us Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, the history of the Prague Transport Company wrote the date on which the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets rather than a paper ticket.
This can now be purchased by nearly a hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously load it onto their chip card at the infocenters and transportation stations of the company at the stations of Metro, Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztýly, Letýňaly.
The bonds can be purchased from yesterday on the internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than four hundred people.
Those who start using the internet as a way of trading can definitely start to forget about ticket sales at the metro stations, where until now they had to regularly line up to get a normal ticket.
The bonus is purchased online, and the Opencard card is recharged at one of the thirteen subsidiaries of the Municipal Library.
“In these places there is a window with prepared staff at the disposal of passengers that helps interested parties with the purchase via the internet and also with the recharge of the voucher purchased on their card,” said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic bonus on the Opencard on the automated vending machines that are located in some metro halls.
How are these vending machines?
They are red, they remind us of a ticket picking machine and travellers will probably already have seen them at the metro stations of Roztyly, Budějovicka, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Now there are five in the city but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný concluded.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
Using the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Simply enter in it the Opencard chip card and the previously paid bonus will be charged only on it.
Electronic bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
In other words, in the circle trains and bus lines from numbers 300 to 499 that mostly use the inhabitants of the towns of central Bohemia.
“In the trains attached to the integrated transportation of Prague there are checkers equipped with a reading card that will help confirm the validity of the time and the bond zone,” said Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid, which sets the schedules for the collective transportation of Prague.
Circuit buses have their reading cards mounted in the driver’s box office.
When entering, it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany him with the Opencard in the intended place on the side of the Box.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the bonus.
“If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonuses, there is nothing easier than requesting the driver for this information,” Drápal said.
Passengers who do not travel on riding buses and do not remember when the voucher’s validity ends, can go to the vending machines where cards are reloaded.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown information about the validity of your document.
