Speaking asleep
Some children talk at night.
I’m not referring to those who wake up very awake, telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk while asleep.
The first time it happens maybe you get scared, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somnilochios.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I’m sure more than one has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon may appear very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once in the month...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause to determine its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (being asleep) or sleepwalking, but it doesn’t have to be so.
As we mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stressful situations or overexcitation.
Anyway, it is a poorly studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or quite the opposite (screams, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him out in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (e.g. if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child much before going to bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid shows or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With children who are very nervous and who have a lot of trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner calm.
This will enable the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
Once sleepiness appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that has happened.
