The interview - Blood is Safe Again
Héma-Québec was celebrating its 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to be happy because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained public trust that had been seriously hesitated by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and the discontent of the public, the Government of Canada conducted in February 1994 a public survey, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, aiming to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a disaster should no longer be reproduced.
While Judge Krever was late in presenting his relationship, certain provinces then created a committee aimed at planning a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Society with blood to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, nearly 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, recalled Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
After making many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence,” he says before proudly claiming that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the population in Quebec had now confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary nevertheless recalls that “trust is extremely fragile.”
Since its creation, on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we witnessed the birth of numerous cases in Europe of the human variant of the crazy cow disease, a new variant of the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells Décary.
And we didn’t know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations in the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we don’t know and when a serious disease can emanate from that, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob’s disease which is characterized by a brain degeneration that inevitably leads to death, we institute exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been shown without any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied was meaningful.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleidic acid tests that allow the presence of the virus to be detected directly in the blood of donors rather than that of antibodies against the virus, which were founded in the tests used so far.
Nucleid acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
We have thus substantially reduced the risk that certain donors are infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements significantly lowered the risk of getting AIDS by a blood transfusion.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
“This means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before anyone gets infected with HIV.
Thus, since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will pass more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I think you can nowadays receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without worries,” says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the Western Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
One must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary pursues before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for sufficient supply.
" Needs are increasing because the population is aging.
As the most aggressive anti-cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which on average regroups only 3 per cent of Quebecers eligible for blood donation. "
All people with good health, 18 years of age and who meet the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
Needlessness is very rare.
But members of this donor network must be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it’s hard to convince people to donate their blood, but especially to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since today’s life is very unrestrained, we rarely find the time to spend an hour to donate your blood,” said Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered biomedical waste is filled with a rich blood of stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We have celebrated a few weeks ago, placing on the bank our thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood and it is expected to take more than a thousand of these a year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood-taking program as very popular.
" Many moms are disappointed not being able to enjoy this," since Héma-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
