In his September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice President and Director of Canadian Miner Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold states that the largest gold company in the world tried a six-million-dollar defamation proceeding against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of persecution for defamation, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely concealed by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, the best way to hold a public debate would be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his own?
The outcome of the litigation is of little importance, so the authors and the publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers held by the miner's almost bottomless pockets.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will cuddle the opposition and frighten anyone who dares to examine the matter again.
If Barrick Gold had really wanted a public debate, it was in front of public opinion that he would have had to present his vision of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done for change of ideas and not for strokes.
It was therefore sufficient for the miner to open up its books, its files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and the financing of independent search teams that would have been able to clarify the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can call for a "public" debate by despising his views?
According to the Vice President, it seems that this word refers only to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
