Psychology of Overlappings: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological-economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
The scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups was playing lottery, the other was participating in an auction and in the meantime the active brain areas of the participants in the experiment were examined by the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI).
In both games the participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the brain cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the “self-award” mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention to not provoke an intense stratum reaction.
To support his theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply communicated the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 prize.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction, the group members even lost that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the hypothesis of the neurologists, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For those until now explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped solve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation,” stated Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When Should You Go to the Doctor?
In the world, about 500 million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected is estimated at one hundred thousand in this country, but only seven thousand are treated because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms resemble a lot; they are characteristic of liver infection and yellowness, but their pathogens and the diseases caused are very different.
Hepatitis viruses in dependence on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vaginal mood, saliva).
It is recommended for travellers to be protected by vaccine against viruses A and B, against C there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by a general poor condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, on the skin and on the white of the eyes, yellowness appears, excrement becomes light, dark urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Annually, a million people worldwide die from cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and often the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early recognition, systematic medical monitoring is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who carry tattoos.
Currently, around 200 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory check as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease is healed if discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress contagion and prevent cancer.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt less to those who believe in God?
According to the results of a recent investigation, religious faith has a soothing effect that also relieved the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in how it influences human pain, the British newspaper Telegraph reported.
As part of this unique experiment, they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was verified that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in the series of researches in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate alongside the academics.
The analysis took place as follows; they fixed a sparking instrument to the left hand of the patient, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their gaze on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, the work of Sassoferrato from the 17th century and the Lady of Leonardo da Vinci's Armiño from the 15th century.
The researchers had hoped that the show of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo’s oil because it was not too different from the other, and thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour on a MRI scanner, receiving in that period 20 electrical shocks in four successive parts while watching either the religious theme painting or the other.
Catholics claimed that by looking at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as people "protected", "reassured themselves and in their heart reigned peace."
When they looked at the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any such shocking image you can achieve a similar effect with atheists as well, you just have to find the right image.
“We should find the portrait of a person they feel very positively for, like for a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
“The exercise of faith should and in many cases truly changes our personality,” Wright added.
After these formidable results there remains a single question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the faithful were shown the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of his size?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
