The smart car mimics the beehive’s flight
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of obstacle sensors existing in nature?
For example, the beehives.
In a surprising project presented at the CEATEC in Japan, the beehives gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the robotic steering system of nature-imitating BR23C cars, to which they gave the characteristics of beehives, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each beehive creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, technology director of RP and development and research.
They play an important role in the composite eyes of beehives that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, the engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
This identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle's microprocessor that immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot mimics the movements of the beehole, changes the direction by rotating the wheels to the extent necessary.
Unlike any existing system today, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If it weren't so, the vehicle's robot wouldn't be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all kinds of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should reflect what a beehole does to avoid other beehole.
This process should be done in an open and closed eyes.
However, unlike beehives, the movement cannot be directed upward, downward or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for beehives to avoid other beehives, here they used only rotary movement and acceleration as a possibility for the car robot in addition to braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and their energy density is higher, meaning they have a longer life than that of lithium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the data processing capacity, let alone that of storage.
This apparatus in every second should only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store these data or react with an instinctive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No gigabyte memory or megabyte memory is needed.
This is the first step towards developing technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which, according to Nissan’s calculations, will be able to be incorporated into mass-made models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding the obstacles existing on his way.
