The written version of the $700 billion financial bailout package, which will be implemented in several phases, has been prepared to purchase bad bank credits.
In the first phase half of the money will be spent.
According to East Coast schedule during the new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement around the $700 billion financial bailout package in total, after several days of discussion, Reuters reported.
We have made significant progress,” said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic president of the U.S. Congress, saying that the deal is only formalized in one document.
The commitment made on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, talking about the outcome of the compromise said: this program will work and be efficient, but further measures are needed. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving Wall Street, but about turning the carriage of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets, i.e. Sunday before 8 a.m., according to Washington time (i.e. before 2 a.m. Monday morning, according to Central Europe time), without causing a spectacular leap in the stock markets.
On the bill called the 2008 Emergency Law for Economic Stabilization, Monday will first vote the U.S. Congress and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted with Pelosi and then the White House also celebrated the news about the deal.
We are pleased with the progress made overnight and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy,” White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program is different from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend all the $700 billion to buy securities of poor-quality credit funds.
Now only half of the $700 billion can be spent, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, the Ministry of Finance will buy credit, poorly qualified fund securities and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president’s decision.
This program will be controlled by a special body, in which the President of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion could be spent after a new Congressional decision.
According to the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy bad credits, mortgages and securities of credit fund securities, as well as other "poisonous" type credits.
The purchase can be made on auctions or directly - competent persons of the ministry informed.
The law allows affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the finance portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson stated: “The law ensures the necessary financial means, which can reach even $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the U.S. financial system, deal with the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance, or the prevention of risks that could lead to the collapse of some major financial institutions.”
We do everything we need to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it,” he added.
Instead, heads of banks who are in trouble and await state aid will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensation, which the American slang simply calls gold parachutes.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and limitations depend on the form of aid from the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry purchases in the context of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on gold parachutes, unless the bank’s failed boss retires.
By purchasing bad credits directly, the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that bosses’ compensation is not exaggerated.
In addition to the foregoing, existing gold parachute contracts will not be changed, the limitations concern only new contracts to encourage participation in the programme as well.
This is the first case in U.S. history that will be in force with a legal limitation on the income of CEOs, said Democrat Barney Frank, chairman of the congressional committee, responsible for financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the program, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, since they can ultimately even make profits from the transaction as soon as the economy is recovered and with it the bank.
According to the bill in the next five years, the president will have to submit to Congress a proposal on how to repay the losses of the financial sector to taxpayers.
Of course, on both sides there were those who expressed their reservations regarding the project.
This is not what American citizens entrusted to us, that is, taxpayer dollars are not being protected,” said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
Her Ohio Democratic colleague Mary Kaptur said the measures urged him the same as those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices rose by 0.1 percent compared to last month’s prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007’s prices – the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose 1.1 percent from July 2008 and declined 3.9 percent from the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose by 0.7 percent from the previous month and by 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial sales prices rose only to a minimum, with 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry rose slightly, up 0.1 percent from July.
The greatest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), due first of all to a 4.6 percent monthly increase in bags and belts and a 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector (1.4 percent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum extent - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
The prices of papermaking, publishers and printers did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry, prices increased between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water representing an important weight within domestic trade, a 0.3 percent increase was recorded in August, first as a result of the effect of the rise in official prices starting July 1.
In a twelve-month comparison - in domestic sales of the processing industry - the greatest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 percent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
Prices declined in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally prices increased by 10.2 percent.
Prices of electricity, gas, heat and water supplies exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices rose by 0.3 percent, in the energy sector and intermediary sectors there was no change over the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the highest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and the intermediate industry (16.8 percent).
In consumer goods producing branches there was a decline of 6.8 percent and in investment goods of 1.4 percent.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF rose 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in a month decreased by 1.7 percent from the euro and by 7.1 percent from the dollar, compared to August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 percent from the euro and 15.9 percent from the dollar.
