Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has begun in Paris, its host is France, which this year is also president of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, MEP of the European People’s Party for Fidesz, in her message addressed to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that beat Roma children and is also the biggest obstacle to the prevailing foundation of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for jobs, social affairs and equal opportunities.
Representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European organisations for the protection of social rights attended the meeting.
Járóka - according to the press office of the Fidesz group of deputies in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Roma are left out of the labour market first because of their low level of education.
“Most of the young Roma have not finished middle education and due to the poor quality of basic education, only an insignificant portion can obtain a university diploma.”
Járóka further emphasized that education, as a fundamental human rights, plays a decisive role in the prevailing foundation of other human rights as well.
Investing in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the MEP, these issues need to be widely aware of both Roma and non-Gypsies.
For the sooner a Roma student begins school, the more chances they will have to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumer taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
“Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be assured the right to a quality education and guarantee the abolition of segregated and low-level education,” said Jároka.
According to the MEP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to accelerate immediately the processes of school segregation, for which the correct compliance with existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is of fundamental importance.
“We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility that guarantees democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens,” said Járóka.
The aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organized annually since last year’s Berlin meeting in the sign of the “European Year for Equal Opportunities” is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at the European and national levels of the Member States.
