Mp3 readers under charge, put hearing at risk
Listening to high-volume music for a long period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing injuries.
This is what the European Commission mentions, which in a statement released in Brussel cites the opinion of the Scientific Commission on the Emerging and Recently Identified Health Risk (Cssseri) of the European Union, published today.
“From this scientific opinion – read in the note – it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable music devices weekly for more than an hour a day with the high-volume apparatus risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity.”
“I am concerned that such a high number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and high-acoustic cell phones can unconsciously ruin their ears in an irremediable way,” said Meglena Kuneva.
“Of the scientific evidence – follows the responsibility Ue – a clear risk emerges and we must react quickly.
What counts is to raise awareness to consumers and render this public domain information.
We must also reexamine the existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion, so that they are broadly effective and have the way with the new technology."
Bruxel had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the widespread use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise that causes.
“Scientists,” concludes executive Ue, “confirm that it is of concern and the European Commission will now consider together with member states and stakeholders what measures could eventually be taken to better protect children and adolescents from noise exposure from portable musical devices and related devices.”
Currently, there is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100 dB, but concern increases as hearing damage can result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and noise exposure time.
In its opinion, the Scientific Committee notes that if users of portable music devices listen to music at a high volume (more than 89 decibels) for only 5 hours a week, they exceed the current limit on maximum noise granted in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after a period of 5 years.
It means that it affects 5-10% of users of such devices and the number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the Ue.
