Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources on which the big ones look like Chevron.
The possibility of collecting energy from sea movements has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s, along with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When oil prices were low in 1980, the idea of taking advantage of marine energy was turned away, but now that environmental cases and the new oil rise are giving momentum to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated by 2007 that 15 percent of the world’s electricity needs could be covered by implants that exploit the movement of sea waves.
This amount would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And there would be currents and tides.
Giants to attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 sealed an agreement to build an implant in Northern Portugal.
When the intention was announced, it seemed a revolutionary step.
Two years away to bet on marine energy are always more and among these companies that have always voted for traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying technology on ocean energy – said the spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil colony to the Wall Street Journal – and is evaluating the possibility of cooperating with us.”
